    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i'm also worried about the soil quality in general. it feels kind of depleted like something is eating up all the good stuff before the plants can even get to it. how do i know if the ph is off or if something else is just stealing the nutrients?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A soil that feels depleted, like a hungry patch of ground, is a common problem, and it can be due to several things, not just a single culprit. To check the pH, you'll need a simple soil testing kit, which is the most reliable way to know if the soil is too acidic or alkaline. If the pH is good, then the issue might be nutrient lockout, where even if the nutrients are present, the plants can't absorb them—this is where soil microbes and organic matter come in. Adding plenty of compost is a great way to improve soil structure and encourage beneficial microbial life, which helps unlock those nutrients.",
      "source": "target",
